&gt; &gt; JUnit for writing unittests. But I have a question which I hope
&gt; some of you
&gt; &gt; can help me with - it&#39;s regarding testing private/protected
&gt; methods and how
&gt; &gt; to organize my test package.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; First the package. I have read to articles regarding test (&quot;Junit best
&gt; &gt; practices&quot; from JavaWorld and &quot;Incremental development with Ant
&gt; and JUnit&quot;
&gt; &gt; from developerWorks). In the JBT article Andy Schneider advice
&gt; you to keep
&gt; &gt; tests in the same location as the source code. And in the Incremental...
&gt; &gt; article Malcolm Davis advice you to make a separate package.
&gt; Which approach
&gt; &gt; is the best to use?
&gt; &gt;
&gt;
&gt; it is better to make separate package. when we can identify as
&gt; two separate
&gt; components like source code and test code it is better to keep them as two
&gt; different components from configuration management point of view.
&gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; I must admit that I like the idea of making a separate package but then
&gt; &gt; again - how do I then test private and protected methods? And
&gt; if I keep the
&gt; &gt; tests in the same location as the source code - who do I then
&gt; test private
&gt; &gt; methods?
&gt; &gt;
&gt;
&gt; we cant test private and protected methods directly.
&gt; we need to find the public methods, which are using those
&gt; protected and private
&gt; methods and test that public methods is enough. Still it is not
&gt; sufficient.
&gt;
&gt; one thing the developer can do is, he can change the private and
&gt; protected to
&gt; public and test them. after that he can change back to private
&gt; and protected
&gt; respectively. but this is not that much good idea.
&gt;
&gt; still we need to find the exact way.
&gt;
